snippet.textDisplay:
To be honest though, if you are young and healthy and never ever come in to contact with elderly people or immune suppressed people, right now is probably a hella good time to travel, if you want to look at a bridge or a tower or a landmark or something. But if you did that, you should still consciously avoid, not just elderly and immune suppressed people, but anyone connected to them. If your best friend is following the social distancing policy, and only hangs out with you and his/her grandma, and you go around looking at bridges and towers and come back, you should wait like what? At the very least a full on month or even several months of absolutely no symptoms before you even meet that best friend again, because you can have it and have no symptoms show for several weeks, and be passing it on during those several weeks of no symptoms, and that is what makes it so dangerous, especially to the elderly. But, if you have no friends and always keep to yourself and you have always wanted to go see a specific mountain, or a water fall, or a trail, or a bridge or something, now just might be the best chance you will ever get to go.


If you went out to go look at a bridge or a mountain right now, I kind of doubt you would come across people any way, and as far as we know this thing isn't just going around spreading by air.
